To find the maximum value of the given determinant, we can expand it as follows:

\begin{align*}
&\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 + \sin \theta & 1 \\ 1 + \cos \theta & 1 & 1 \end{vmatrix}\\
=& 1 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 1 + \sin \theta & 1 \\ 1 & 1 \end{vmatrix} - 1 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 + \cos \theta & 1 \end{vmatrix} + 1 \cdot \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 + \sin \theta \\ 1 + \cos \theta & 1 \end{vmatrix}
\end{align*}

Evaluating the determinants of the $2 \times 2$ submatrices, we get:

\begin{align*}
=& 1 \cdot \bigl[(1 + \sin \theta) - 1\bigr] - 1 \cdot \bigl[1 - (1 + \cos \theta)\bigr] + 1 \cdot \bigl[1 - (1 + \cos \theta)(1 + \sin \theta)\bigr]\\
=& 1 \cdot \sin \theta + 1 \cdot \cos \theta + 1 \cdot \bigl[1 - (1 + \sin \theta)(1 + \cos \theta)\bigr]\\
=& \sin \theta + \cos \theta + 1 - (1 + \sin \theta)(1 + \cos \theta)\\
=& \sin \theta + \cos \theta + 1 - 1 - \sin \theta - \cos \theta - \sin \theta \cos \theta\\
=& - \sin \theta \cos \theta
\end{align*}

Using the trigonometric identity $\sin(2\theta) = 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta,$ we can rewrite the determinant as:

\begin{align*}
= - \frac{1}{2} \sin(2\theta)
\end{align*}

To find the maximum value of this expression, we note that the maximum value of $\sin(2\theta)$ is $1$.  Therefore, the maximum value of the given determinant is $\boxed{-\frac{1}{2}}$.
